10244nam a22013095i 9783110719932DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021933281  a97831107199327 a10.1515/97831107199322doi  a(DE-B1597)567639  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aSCI0500002bisacsh00aEthics in Nanotechnology. pEthics in Nanotechnology ; Social Sciences and Philosophical Aspects /ced. by Gunjan Jeswani, Marcel Van de Voorde. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (XLII, 363 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEthics in Nanotechnology00tFrontmatter -- tPreface: Converging technologies from the nanoscale require enhanced ethics -- tForewords -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Overall vision of ethics in nanotechnology developments -- tEmbedding ethics in nanomedicine: Europe acted promptly -- tList of contributing authors -- tAbout the editors -- tPart I: International reflection -- t1 Toward a revitalized vision of ethics and safety for the revolutionary nanotechnologies -- tPart II: Nanotechnology expansions raising ethical concerns -- t2 Nanotechnology in agrifood sector: Ethical, regulatory, and governance landscape in EU -- t3 Defining nanoscience and nano-ethics: why does the future need nanoproducts? -- t4 Streaching the notion of moral responsibility in nanoelectronics by appying AI -- t5 Risk screening tools for engineered nanomaterials -- t6 Nano-ethics: A view from a developing country -- tPart III: Nanotechnology philosophy: Dilemmas and ethical issues -- t7 Christian thinking and acting in nanotechnologies: Reflection based on the principles and values of the Social Teaching of the Church based on apps concerning old people -- t8 Ethical imperatives towards the development prospects of the triad of Dentistry 4.0, dental engineering, and nanoengineering -- t9 Debate: Nanoparticles – a blessing or a curse? -- t10 The broad spectrum of ethics in nanoscience and nanotechnology: A reflection from scientific research to the media -- tPart IV: Ethical recommendations for promising technology -- t11 From big statements to anecdotal and incremental regulation: Nanotechnology and the law in the EU -- t12 Emerging nanoregulations: zapping the mythical absence of nanotechnology law -- t13 Contemporary global bioethical challenges of innovation in nanoscience and nanotechnologies. Contributing to the Sustainable Development Goals -- t14 Nanotechnology and ethics in dialogue -- t15 Revitalizing nano-ethics: Nanotechnology at the center of nano-ethics -- t16 Reflections on nano-ethics the way forward toward equitable and safe nanotechnology for all -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith nanotechnology being a relatively new field, the questions regarding safety and ethics are steadily increasing with the development of the research. This book aims to give an overview on the ethics associated with employing nanoscience for products with everyday applications. The risks as well as the regulations are discussed, and an outlook for the future of nanoscience on a manufacturer’s scale and for the society is provided. Ethics in nanotechnology is a valuable resource for, philosophers, academicians and scientist, as well as all other industry professionals and researchers who interact with emerging social and philosophical ethical issues on routine bases. It is especially for deep learners who are enthusiastic to apprehend the challenges related to nanotechnology and ethics in philosophical and social education. This book presents an overview of new and emerging nanotechnologies and their societal and ethical implications. It is meant for students, academics, scientists, engineers, policy makers, ethicist, philosophers and all stakeholders involved in the development and use of nanotechnology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aEthik. 4aMaterialwissenschaften. 4aNanotechnologie. 4aSozialwissenschaften. 7aSCIENCE / Nanoscience.2bisacsh1 aAlbin, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBardea, Amos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBossa, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBovassi, Giulia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalster, Geert van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobrzańska, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobrzański, Lech B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobrzański, Leszek A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvrard, Albert Ed., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFadeel, Bengt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeitshans, Ilise L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranken, Remy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía Gómez, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrieger, Khara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGupta, Nidhi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansen, Steffen Foss, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHongladarom, Soraj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHounkonnou, Mahouton Norbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsigonis, Panagiotis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaner,